The Nigeria Police said a total of 1,736 violators of the presidential directive on lockdown have been convicted so far out of the 1,909 suspects arraigned in the Federal Capital Territory, Abuja. This was revealed by the FCT Commissioner of Police, FCT, CP Bala Ciroma while giving an update on the enforcement of the presidential lockdown order. The Commissioner stated that 13 mobile courts were set up, while 145 suspected violators were discharged and 28 cases, adjourned . He explained that the convicted violators were sentenced to community service or asked to pay a fine. CP Ciroma also urged traditional, religious and community leaders to complement the effort of the government, to contain the spread of the Coronavirus, by using their influence to educate and enlighten people on the need to observe the presidential lockdown order. The CP further stated that in compliance with the directives of the Inspector-General of Police, the Command has focused its crime fighting effort on crimes like armed robbery, Kidnapping, robbery, one chance robbery theft, housebreaking within this period. He revealed that 43 suspects have been arrested I’m connection with the crimes mentioned above; with one locally made Ak47 rifle, eight locally made pistol, one Tavor rifle, one Dane gun, 37 ammunition, eleven cutlasses/knives/cutters, three phones and ten cars recovered.